<br>
A cold gust of winter wind batters her nearly naked form, and she redoubles her efforts to wake the house.  To no avail.  Shivering with cold, she grasps the handle of the door, and opens it slowly.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  &quot;Hallooo?  Anybody home?&quot; <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Silence greets her calls, and she enters the kitchen and closes the door behind her.  The house is warmer than the cold outside, but she can still see her breath before her.  It is strange, but it appears to have been left suddenly.  Many chairs are placed around the kitchen, and a pot of water on the stove has a thin sheet of ice crystals on it's surface.  A jar of cocoa and a spoon are nearby, as if the person making the cocoa simply disappeared.  Mircha attempts to ponder these things, but the long night, and her wrestle with the mermaid, the siren, and the merman, have left her utterly exhausted.  <br>
<br>
She drags her tired body into the next room, and her mouth drops.  A handful of pixies are assembled in various uncomfortable looking pixie poses, on a large orange sofa.  There is a coloured light that flashes on them, and a noise coming from the the other side of the room.  She looks warily at the pixies, but they are completely indifferent to her presence.  She moves into the room, and spying a large chair, goes to it, and sinks into it with a grateful sigh.  Curling up into a ball, she pulls her cloak around her, and her eyes droop shut.  The noise is still there, and the lights flash behind her eyes.  The noise is language of some kind, and she hears the words</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> &quot;Bill Nye...science guy...&quot;. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Must be a poem, she thinks, and starts to hum softly to herself.  Half-asleep, she is unaware of the tune she is humming, or of the tear that falls from her eye on her way into slumber at last.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
